Nope, honestly I have no idea where I should start from :(
Any advice ?

Hi @andompesta,

Most likely this is an invalid ONNX model and this will be a bug to report to the Torch project. The root cause is probably there is a node that has inputs bound to different types (float and double) when it is expected to be homogeneous (either both float or both double). This is possible only due to model export/conversion. Since the node names seem to be missing, I ll try and find which node is the problematic node. You can use the info to report the bug. I ll update the thread when done.

Hi @andompesta,

I investigated the model. As suspected, it looks like an invalid ONNX model. I annotated the model 
with random names for the node to localize the issue (attached the new model). The issue seems to be in this 'Where' node - 
[Encoder_with_node_names.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/3592567/Encoder_with_node_names.zip)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/64565439-9dabec80-d308-11e9-92c5-4e5d23378d05.png)

'X' for the 'Where' node is of type 'float64' but the input 'Y' (coming from the output of the upstream 'Div' node) is of type 'float32'. This is invalid per op spec - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Where. The inputs 'X' and 'Y' are both bound to type parameter 'T' , meaning that they SHOULD be homogeneous. Please open an issue with the project that helped you get the ONNX model with this information.

FWIW, the ONNX model checker (from the ONNX project) should ideally fail when validating this model. So, I opened an issue there - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2292. Details on how to check an ONNX model may be found here - https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/PythonAPIOverview.md.

Since this is not an ORT issue, closing this issue. Please re-open if you need more clarifications. 
Thanks!

issue.body:
##  Bug

After exporting a simple model using `torch.onnx.export` it is unable to be loaded into onnx runtime due to an invalid graph, which appears to be caused by PyTorch forcing a tensor to be of type double, despite it being explicitly cast to float in the code. 

N.B. the model below is simply a minimal repro of a much more complex model that is failing with the same error.

## To Reproduce

```py
import torch
import onnxruntime as ort

class Test(torch.nn.Module):
            
    def forward(self, x):
        a, b, c = x.shape
        x = x.reshape(a, -1)
        d, e = x.shape
        x = x.reshape(e, -1)
        x = x.to(torch.float32) / torch.tensor(2., dtype=torch.float32)
        return x

body = Test().eval()

data = torch.randn(3, 2, 1)
y = body(data)
model = torch.jit.script(body)

torch.onnx.export(model, (data,), 'tmp.onnx', verbose=True, input_names=['data'], opset_version=13, example_outputs=(y,))
session = ort.InferenceSession("tmp.onnx")

```

```
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fail                                      Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-15-2243707fe8f3> in <module>
     18 # options.log_severity_level = 2
     19 # options.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_ALL
---> 20 session = ort.InferenceSession("tmp.onnx")

/venv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py in __init__(self, path_or_bytes, sess_options, providers, provider_options)
    278 
    279         try:
--> 280             self._create_inference_session(providers, provider_options)
    281         except RuntimeError:
    282             if self._enable_fallback:

/venv/lib/python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py in _create_inference_session(self, providers, provider_options)
    305         session_options = self._sess_options if self._sess_options else C.get_default_session_options()
    306         if self._model_path:
--> 307             sess = C.InferenceSession(session_options, self._model_path, True, self._read_config_from_model)
    308         else:
    309             sess = C.InferenceSession(session_options, self._model_bytes, False, self._read_config_from_model)

Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Load model from tmp.onnx failed:Type Error: Type parameter (T) bound to different types (tensor(double) and tensor(float) in node (Div_17).
```

The verbose output from the export can be found below, the issue seems to be this cast to double 
```%21 : Tensor = onnx::Cast[to=11](%20)```
Note that my explicit cast to float (`%20`) is overridden which appears to be the core issue that needs to be resolved 
```

  %11 : int[] = onnx::Shape(%10) # <string>:7:9
  %12 : Long(device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value={1}]()

  %19 : Tensor = onnx::Reshape(%10, %18) # <ipython-input-14-11296ffcff6e>:10:12
  %20 : Tensor = onnx::Cast[to=1](%19) # <ipython-input-14-11296ffcff6e>:11:12
  %21 : Tensor = onnx::Cast[to=11](%20)

  %23 : Float(2, 3, strides=[3, 1], requires_grad=0, device=cpu) = onnx::Div(%21, %22)
  return (%23)
```

## Expected behavior

The model to loads  into onnx runtime without error

issue.body:
Trying to convert model to ONNX using - 

```
sample_input = (source_id, source_mask)
torch.onnx.export(model, sample_input, 'model.onnx', export_params=True,
                 verbose=True, input_names=['source_ids', 'source_mask'],
                 output_names=['output'], 
                 dynamic_axes={'input' : {0 : 'batch_size'},
                               'output' : {0 : 'batch_size'}
                              },
                  opset_version=11
                 )
```
model does get converted to model.onnx but loading it in ONNXRuntime throws error: 
**_Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Load model from model.onnx failed:Type Error: Type parameter (T) of Optype (Concat) bound to different types (tensor(int64) and tensor(float) in node (Concat_335)._**

code used to load the model in ONNXRuntime - 

```
import onnx
onnx_model = onnx.load("model.onnx")
onnx.checker.check_model(onnx_model, full_check=True)      # no error here

import onnxruntime
ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("model.onnx")        # error

```


Similar issue raised at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1764 suggests some problem with model or in conversion process. 
Kindly help, Thanks!

issue.title: fixing TypeError during loading onnx model.
issue.body:
When exporting a Pytorch model to onnx version of itself, if there is a constant in the model, loading onnx model raises error.  A simple example is given below:

```
import torch
import numpy as np
import torch.nn as nn

import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort


class ExampleModule(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        super().__init__()

    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor):
        x = x - 1.0
        return x


example_module = ExampleModule()
example_in = torch.Tensor([[1, 2, 3, 4], [5, 6, 7, 8]])

torch.onnx.export(example_module,
                  args=(example_in),
                  f="example_module.onnx",
                  input_names=["x"],
                  output_names=["output1"],
                  opset_version = 11,
                  dynamic_axes={
                      'x': {0 : 'batch_size'},
                      'output1': {0 : 'batch_size'},
                  },
                  verbose=True)

model = onnx.load("example_module.onnx")
onnx.checker.check_model(model)

ort_session = ort.InferenceSession("example_module.onnx")
```

`ort.InferenceSession` raises error:
```
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fail                                      Traceback (most recent call last)
Input In [6], in <cell line: 8>()
      5 model = onnx.load("example_module.onnx")
      6 onnx.checker.check_model(model)
----> 8 ort_session = ort.InferenceSession("example_module.onnx")
     10 outputs = ort_session.run(
     11     None,
     12     {
     13         "x": example_in.numpy().astype(np.float32),
     14     },
     15 )
     16 print(example_in)

File ~/anaconda3/envs/k2_sherpa/lib/python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py:335, in InferenceSession.__init__(self, path_or_bytes, sess_options, providers, provider_options, **kwargs)
    332 disabled_optimizers = kwargs['disabled_optimizers'] if 'disabled_optimizers' in kwargs else None
    334 try:
--> 335     self._create_inference_session(providers, provider_options, disabled_optimizers)
    336 except ValueError:
    337     if self._enable_fallback:

File ~/anaconda3/envs/k2_sherpa/lib/python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py:370, in InferenceSession._create_inference_session(self, providers, provider_options, disabled_optimizers)
    368 session_options = self._sess_options if self._sess_options else C.get_default_session_options()
    369 if self._model_path:
--> 370     sess = C.InferenceSession(session_options, self._model_path, True, self._read_config_from_model)
    371 else:
    372     sess = C.InferenceSession(session_options, self._model_bytes, False, self._read_config_from_model)

Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Load model from example_module.onnx failed:Type Error: Type parameter (T) of Optype (Sub) bound to different types (tensor(float) and tensor(double) in node (Sub_1).
```

Hence, I traced exported graph and converted type of problematic tensors from Double to Float. I just multiple these tensors with `torch.ones((1),  dtype=torch.float32)`.
